rd]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Veggietales: Here I Am to Worship\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2011\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Sweetpea's Songs for Girls\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Parents' Choice Award]]: Seasons Best Family Game\n|VeggieTales: Find It!\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|2012\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Hosanna! Today Top Worship Songs for Kids\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|VeggieTales 25 Favorite Bible Songs\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"CBN\" />\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Outstanding Animated Program\n|[[VeggieTales in the House]] Season One\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"Wrap Emmys\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Outstanding Sound Editing\n|[[VeggieTales in the House]] Season Four\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=VeggieTales in the House - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3692064/awards|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tennessee House of Representatives|The Tennessee State House]] Resolution 68 Award: Life Time Achievement in Children's Entertainment \n|[[Mike Nawrocki]] for his 25 years of work on VeggieTales \n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url= https://www.linkedin.com/in/mike-nawrocki-450b465/|title=Mike Nawrocki \u2013 Chief Creative \u2013 Mike Nawrocki Creative, LLC {{!}} LinkedIn |accessdate= July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Best Performer in an Animated Program\n|[[Tress MacNeille]] in [[VeggieTales in the City]]\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2018/2018-daytime-emmy-winners-full-list-creative-arts-awards-news-264817359/|title=2018 Daytime Emmy winners: Full list of Creative Arts Awards winners and nominees|last=Montgomery|first=Daniel|last2=Montgomery|first2=Daniel|date=April 28, 2018|website=GoldDerby|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Related media==\n===Feature-length films===\n*''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2002): Archibald Asparagus stars as [[Jonah]] in this version of the Biblical story. The Veggies learn that God is a God of second chances, and that we need to give second chances too and be compassionate and merciful.<ref name=\"NYTJonah\">{{cite news |last1=Kehr |first1=David |title=FILM IN REVIEW; 'Jonah' -- 'A Veggie Tales Movie' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/movies/film-in-review-jonah-a-veggie-tales-movie.html |accessdate=18 August 2019 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Veggie Tales - Conyers.jpg|thumb|Mr. Lunt, Pa Grape, and Larry the Cucumber at the Celebrate Freedom 2007 concert.]]\n*''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2008): In this second VeggieTales feature film, three lazy wannabe pirates go back in time to the 17th century, to fight real pirates and become heroes in a battle, to rescue a royal family from an evil tyrant. The three slackers learn that a hero doesn't have to be tall, strong, and handsome to be useful.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoesPWDDA\">{{cite web |title=The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_who_dont_do_anything_a_veggietales_movie |website=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n* ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' (TBD): The origin story of VeggieTales hosts Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber reveals how they met, how they got their own show, and answers the question how vegetables and fruit talk. This will be the first film in the series to feature humans. According to Phil Vischer, \"Since ''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' was our [[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|''The'' ''Ten Commandments,'']] ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' would be our ''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]].''<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://philvischer.com/news/what-happened-to-big-idea-part-1/|title=What Happened to Big Idea? (Part 1) - Phil Vischer - Official Blog of VeggieTales Creator|date=2004-11-15|website=Phil Vischer|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>''\"'' The Bob and Larry Movie was originally planned to be the second VeggieTales movie with a released date in late 2005. It was placed into production in early 2002, toward the end of production of ''Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie'' (2002).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2008/januaryweb-only/philvischer.html|title=The More You Preach, the Fewer You Reach|last=Hertz|first=by Todd|website=ChristianityToday.com|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> However, Big Idea Productions fell into bankruptcy in late 2002 and the film was placed on hiatus because it was deemed too expensive. As a result, [[Phil Vischer]] wrote ''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' to replace this movie. In 2008, it was considered to be the sequel to ''The Pirates who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie'', but talks had stalled after the 2008 recession had led to the bankruptcy of VeggieTales owner ''Entertainment Rights'' and ''Classic Media.'' According to Phil Vischer in 2018, \"I have a copy of ''The Bob and Larry'' script on my laptop, but probably won't release it because it is technically owned by Universal and DreamWorks.\" \"It will hopefully be produced in the near future.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n*''Untitled VeggieTales Movie'' (TBD): On March 28, 2019, Vischer and Nawrocki announced at the National Religious Broadcast Convention that they were developing a screenplay with Universal Studios for a new Veggietales movie. Universal Studios wants the film to be a bible story similar to ''Jonah: A Veggietales Movie'', so the film will not be ''The Bob and Larry Movie''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/philvischer/status/1241348735386427393|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The release date has not been announced.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |title=Phil Vischer on Twitter: \"New TV series in production with TBN. New movie in development at Universal. I'm involved in both!\" |url=https://twitter.com/philvischer/status/1111372778039476230 |website=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stage production===\n''VeggieTales Live'' is a series of stage shows based on the ''VeggieTales'' videos. The first stage series was part of a two-year agreement with [[iHeartMedia|Clear Channel]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hettrick|first1=Scott|title='VeggieTales' hit the stage|url=https://variety.com/2001/digital/features/veggietales-hit-the-stage-1117802949/|accessdate=October 16, 2017|work=Variety|date=July 18, 2001}}</ref> Six versions of the shows have been staged. The shows have toured across the U.S. and at theme parks including [[Dollywood]] and [[Silver Dollar City]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/veggietales-live-happy-birthday-bob--larry-tour-returns-this-fall-with-first-time-show-dates-for-west-coast-221632901.html |title=VeggieTales Live! Happy Birthday Bob & Larry Tour Returns This Fall With First-Time Show Dates For West Coast |author=Big Idea Entertainment|date=August 29, 2013 |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Video games===\nBig Idea, and its successors, have released ''VeggieTales'' themed games on various platforms including PC, Macintosh, iOS, and Android. Applications include games revolving around specific ''VeggieTales'' episodes (such as the PlayStation 2 release of ''LarryBoy and the Bad Apple'') to new content revolving around various ''VeggieTales'' characters.\n\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title              = VeggieTales\n| image              = VeggieTales 2014 logo.png\n| caption            = Logo (as of August 2014)\n| developer          = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=Various, including\n  |1=[[Papaya Studio]] |2=DC Studios |3=Fingerprint Network |4=[[Digital Praise]]}}\n| genre              = [[Christian video game|Christian]]<br/>[[Adventure game|Adventure]]<br/>[[Educational video game|Edutainment]]\n| platforms          = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[VideoNow]]\n| creator            = [[Big Idea Entertainment]]\n| first release version  = ''The Mystery of Veggie Island''\n| first release date     = September 3, 2002\n| latest release version = ''Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music''\n| latest release date    = March 19, 2012\n}}\n\n====Macintosh/PC====\n#''The Mystery of Veggie Island'' (September 15, 2002)<ref name=\"VG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020305134828/http://www.hive4media.com:80/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|title=Veggie Tales Headed for CD-ROM|website=[[hive4media.com]]|archivedate=March 5, 2002|date=February 19, 2002|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n#''Veggie Carnival'' (October 15, 2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/VeggieTales-Veggie-Carnival-Jewel-Case-Pc/dp/B00006JK51/ref=sr_1_8?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-8 |title=VeggieTales: Veggie Carnival (Jewel Case) \u2013 PC: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Jonah: A VeggieTales Game'' (November 2002)<ref name=\"VG\"/>\n#''VeggieTales Creativity City'' (February 4, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Creativity-City-PC-Game/dp/B000098XNE/ref=sr_1_2?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-2 |title=Veggie Tales Creativity City (PC Game): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes'' (September 30, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Minnesota-Coconut-Jewel-Pc/dp/B0002BJSLE/ref=pd_sim_sbs_vg_3 |title=Veggie Tales: Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes (Jewel Case): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Super Silly Fun!'' (December 15, 2005)<ref>{{cite web|author=ValuSoft |url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Super-Silly-Cd-rom-PC/dp/B001E91ELA/ref=sr_1_12?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-12 |title=Veggie Tales Super Silly Fun! Cd-rom: Video Games |date=August 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Dance Dance Dance'' (December 2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Bigideass-Veggietales-Dance-Pad-Game/dp/B001D6K2B2|title=Bigideas's Veggietales Dance Dance Dance Dance Pad Game: Video Games|access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====PlayStation 2 and Game Boy Advance games====\n#''[[LarryBoy and the Bad Apple]]'' (August 1, 2006)<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggietales-Larry-Boy-Apple-Playstation-2/dp/B000F7CECU/ref=sr_1_1?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-1 |title=Veggietales: Larry Boy and the Bad Apple \u2013 PlayStation 2: Big Idea: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====iOS====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id492022025?ls=1&mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/veggietales-spotisode-collection/id499459063?mt=8 |title=Watch and Find \u2013 VeggieTales Games and Video Clips \u2013 A Fingerprint Network App on the App Store on iTunes |publisher=iTunes Store |date=December 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id509109422?mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Android====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)\n\n====Other systems====\n''VeggieTales'' games shipped pre-bundled in the  [[Game Wave Family Entertainment System]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Jordan|title=Christians Loved Canada's Failed Video Game Console|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/3k5d58/christians-loved-canadas-failed-video-game-console-game-wave|accessdate=December 26, 2017|work=Motherboard|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music and audio CDs===\n{{main|List of VeggieTales albums}}\n\nThere have been over 45 musical albums released that tie into either ''VeggieTales'' characters or videos. While some of the albums are merely compilations of songs from the various videos (including albums entitled ''Larry-Boy Soundtrack'', ''[[A Very Veggie Easter]]'', and ''25 Favorite Very VeggieTunes''), others contain completely original content such as stories or songs performed by Phil Vischer, Mike Nawrocki, and the other ''VeggieTales'' voice talent (such as ''Bob and Larry's Campfire Songs'', ''Christian Hit Music'', and ''Bob and Larry Sing the 80's'').\n\n===Merchandise===\nOn February 10, 2011, Big Idea Entertainment announced several new product promotions, including partnerships with [[Chick-fil-A]] (kids meal promotions), American Puzzle Company (wooden puzzles and trains), CTI Industries (mylar and latex balloons), Tabbies (index tabs, stickers, temporary tattoos and wall clings), Victory Designs (children's guitars), and Zoobies (plush pillows and blankets).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licensemag.com/license-global/big-idea-grows-veggietales-brand |title=Big Idea Grows VeggieTales Brand |publisher=License! Global |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=October 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Books and Comics ====\n{{Main|List of VeggieTales books}}\nIn June 2014, B&H Kids announced plans to produce a ''VeggieTales'' comic with [[Big Idea Productions]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]].<ref>{{cite press release|author1=B&H Kids|title=B&H Kids and Veggitales Team to Create New Line of Comic Books|url=http://www.bhpublishinggroup.com/press-release/bh-kids-and-veggietales-team-to-create-a-new-line-of-comic-books|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.veggietales.com/ }}\n*[http://www.ceganmo.com/2008/11/veggietales.html VeggieTales] at CEGAnMo.com\n*{{IMDb title|id=0865856|title=VeggieTales}}\n{{VeggieTales}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}{{Netflix original ended series}}{{TBN}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veggietales}}\n[[Category:VeggieTales| ]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1993 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Big Idea Entertainment television series]]\n[[Category:Christian animation]]\n[[Category:Christian children's television series]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Classics]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Qubo]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:3078:3100:1cc1:a34e:7a62:b311", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VeggieTales"}
{"title_page": "History of Liao", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Chinese|title=''History of Liao''|t=\u907c\u53f2|s=\u8fbd\u53f2|p=Li\u00e1o Sh\u01d0|poj=Li\u00e2u-s\u00fa}}\nThe '''''History of Liao''''', or '''''Liao Shi''''' ('''''Li\u00e1o Sh\u01d0'''''), is a Chinese historical book compiled officially by the [[Mongol]] [[Yuan dynasty]] (1271\u20131368), under the direction of the historian [[Toqto'a (Yuan dynasty)|Toqto'a]] (Tuotuo), and finalized in 1344.<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\">Xu Elina-Qian, p.22</ref> Based on Khitan's primary sources and other previous official Chinese records, it exposes the [[Khitan people]], Khitan's tribal life and traditions, as well as the official histories of the [[Liao dynasty]] and its successor, the [[Qara Khitai|Western Liao dynasty]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" />\n\n== Main sources ==\n''History of Liao'' of 1344 was compiled using older sources, mainly: \n* the ''Shilu'' \u5be6\u9304 (Veritable Records), completed in the Khitan Liao dynasty (907-1125) under Yel\u00fc Yan \u8036\u5f8b\u513c's direction, no longer extant;\n* a draft ''Liao Shi'', compiled in the Jurchen [[Jin dynasty (1115-1234)|Jin dynasty]] under the direction of an official named Chen Daren \u9673\u5927\u4efb, never published and no longer extant;\n* and several other sources such as the [[Zizhi Tongjian]] (1080's), [[Qidan Guo Zhi]] and other descriptions of the Khitans in the previous dynastic histories ([[Wei Shu]], [[Sui Shu]], ...).\nThe ''Liao Shi'' contains 116 volumes,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> including 30 volumes of Imperial Annals, 32 volumes of Records of Institutions, 8 volumes of Tables, 48 volumes of Biographies and Descriptions, and 1 volume of Glossary of National Language \u570b\u8a9e\u89e3 Guoyijie (the [[Khitan language]]),<ref>{{cite book|title=Chinese History: A Manual|first=Endymion Porter|last=Wilkinson|others=|volume=Volume 52 of Harvard Yenching Institute Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard-Yenching Institute monograph series |issue=Issue 52 of Harvard-Yenching Institute monograph series| ISSN =0073-084X|editor-first=|editor-last=|edition=illustrated, revised|date=|year=2000|publisher=Harvard Univ Asia Center|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERnrQq0bsPYC&pg=PA864&dq=Qinding+Liao+Jin+Yuan+sanshi+guoyujie&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PskPVL60NdLhsATT24Bw&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Qinding%20Liao%20Jin%20Yuan%20sanshi%20guoyujie&f=false|page=864|isbn=0674002490|accessdate=24 April 2014| ref=harv }}</ref><ref>pp. 123-125 Howorth, H. H.. 1881. \"The Northern Frontagers of China. Part V. The Khitai or Khitans\". Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland 13 (2). Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland: 121\u201382. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25196875.</ref><ref name=\"YongPeng2008\">{{cite book|author1=Heming Yong|author2=Jing Peng|title=Chinese Lexicography : A History from 1046 BC to AD 1911: A History from 1046 BC to AD 1911|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NYFBtTUZFxEC&pg=PA382#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=14 August 2008|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-156167-2|pages=382\u2013}}</ref> which is a list of Khitan language words [[Transcription into Chinese characters|transcribed in Chinese characters]]. it is found in Chapter 116 - [https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u907c\u53f2/\u5377116 \u907c\u53f2/\u5377116].\n\n== Creation and reliability ==\nMany Chinese scholars of the time argued that the non-[[Han Chinese|Han]], \"barbarian\" Liao dynasty did not merit its own official history, but rather posited that the Liao histories should be an addendum to the history of the [[Song dynasty|Song]], which was ethnically [[Han Chinese]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> This was part of the larger dispute between the Mongol court and the Chinese literati scholars, in which the Chinese political theory whereby only one dynasty could be deemed legitimate at a time clashed with the Mongol's beliefs to the contrary.<ref>Hok-lam Chan, p.73</ref> Due to this dispute between two different political cultures, the ''Liao Shi'', as well as the histories of the concurrent [[Jin dynasty (1115-1234)|Jin]] and Song dynasties, was not officially compiled until 1343\u20131344, when the pro-Chinese Chief Councillor Toqto'a took up the pre-Yuan histories project again. In its final form, this project conceded to the Mongol court's desire to treat the Liao, Jin, and Song as equally legitimate dynasties. The compilation of the ''Liao Shi'' was finished in one year<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> by imperial historians, although without undergoing any but the most minimal of proofreadings.<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> Because of this, the ''Liao Shi'' and the other two pre-Yuan histories are known for their technical errors, lack of precision, inconsistencies in transcribing non-Chinese terms and names, and over-lapping subject matter.  Qing scholars [[Qian Daxin]] and Zhao Yi noted inconsistencies in the '''''History of Liao''''' in their works ''Study of the Discrepancies in the Twenty-two Standard Histories'' \u5eff\u4e8c\u53f2\u5284\u8a18 and ''Critical Notes on the Twenty-two Histories'' \u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\u53f2\u5284\u8a18.{{sfnp|Chan|2014|page=91}}\n<!-- Inside -->\nNonetheless, the ''Liao Shi'' provides a large amount of knowledge on Khitan's imperium's tribal politics and traditions. Since Yel\u00fc Yan's ''Shilu'' and Chen Daren's ''Liao Shi'' have been lost,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> Toqto'a's ''Liao Shi'' is the only extant Chinese-style historical record of the Khitan empire.\n\n== Editions ==\nThe work of collation and punctuation have been done several times,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23\">Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23</ref> by example in the Qianlong edition, the Nanjian edition, the Beijian edition, Baina edition and the Daoguang edition.<br />The nowadays commonly use edition is the Zhonghua Shuju Press edited ''Liao Shi'', under direction of the Khitan studies' specialists [[Feng Jiasheng]] and [[Chen Shu (scholar)|Chen Shu]], and based on the Baina edition. This Zhonghua Shuju Press version and its annotations also refer to other historical sources such as the [[Cefu Yuangui]], [[Zizhi Tongjian]], [[Xu Zizhi Tongjian Changbian]], [[Jiu Tangshu|Jiu]] & [[Xin Tangshu]], [[Jiu Wudai Shi|Jiu]] & [[Xin Wudai Shi]], [[History of Song|Song Shi]], [[Jin Shi]], [[Qidan Guo Zhi]] and [[Liao Wenhui]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23\" /><ref name=\"LS, 1974\">\u907c\u53f2, \u8131\u8131, \u4e2d\u534e\u4e66\u5c40, 1974.</ref>\n\nThe History of Liao was translated into [[Manchu language|Manchu]] as {{MongolUnicode|\u1869\u1820\u1873\u182f\u1873\u1836\u1823\u1823<br />\u1864\u1860\u1875\u1860\u1828 {{zwj}}\u200d\u1873<br />\u1830\u1860\u1869\u1860\u1875\u1873}} (Wylie: ''Dailiyan gurun i suduri'', [[Transliterations of Manchu|M\u00f6llendorff]]: ''Dailiyan gurun i suduri'').\n\nThe [[Qing dynasty]] [[Qianlong Emperor]] erroneously identified the Khitan people and their language with the [[Solons]], leading him to use the [[Solon language]] to \"correct\" Chinese character transcriptions of Khitan names in the History of Liao in his \"Imperial Liao Jin Yuan Three Histories National Language Explanation\" (\u6b3d\u5b9a\u907c\u91d1\u5143\u4e09\u53f2\u570b\u8a9e\u89e3 Qinding Liao Jin Yuan sanshi guoyujie) project.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Crossley |first= Pamela Kyle |last2= Rawski |first2= Evelyn S. |date= Jun 1993 |title= A Profile of The Manchu Language in Ch'ing History |jstor= 2719468|journal= Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies |publisher= Harvard-Yenching Institute |volume=  53|issue= 1 |page=99 |doi= 10.2307/2719468 }}</ref>\n\nQianlong's \"corrections\" ended up compounding the errors and making the transcription of some foreign words even worse.<ref>{{cite book|title=Notices of the Medi\u00e6val Geography and History of Central and Western Asia| first=E.|last=Bretschneider|volume=|year=1876|edition=|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner & Company|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R98-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA6 |pages=5\u20136 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref> Marshall Broomhall wrote that ''So unscientific was this work that the K'ien-lung editions of the Liao, Kin, and Y\u00fcan histories are practically useless.''<ref name=\"Broomhall1910\">{{cite book|author=Marshall Broomhall|title=Islam in China: A Neglected Problem|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ObcNAAAAIAAJ|year=1910|publisher=Morgan & Scott, Limited|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ObcNAAAAIAAJ/page/n116 93]\u201394}}</ref> [[Emil Bretschneider]] demonstrated how the etymologies in the Qianlong edition were incorrect.<ref name=\"Bretschneider2013 2\">{{cite book|author=E. Bretschneider|title=Mediaeval Researches from Eastern Asiatic Sources: Fragments Towards the Knowledge of the Geography and History of Central and Western Asia from the 13th to the 17th Century:|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fc9YAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&dq=sagacity+savants+original+edition+calif+baghdad+correctly+ha+li+fa+uncorrupted+understood+turkish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwr6mZzfLOAhXCSSYKHShZB7EQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-38021-1|pages=182\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe annals are covered in Volumes 1-30 beginning with founder [[Abaoji]] (Taizu) in volumes 1\u20132. Volume 30 covers [[Yel\u00fc Dashi]], who fled and founded of the state of [[Qara Khitai]] also known as the Western Liao at the dissolution of the Liao dynasty. Biran describes  volume 30 of the text as the one of the most important sources for the history of the Qara Khitai.{{sfnp|Biran|2005|page=4}}\n\nTreatises are covered in volumes 31\u201362. The [[Administrative divisions of the Liao dynasty|administrative divisions of the Liao]] are described in volumes 37 through 41 under the title Geography (\u5730\u7406), organized by the five primary level circuits (\u9053). Official posts (\u767e\u5b98) are described in volumes 45\u201348. Standen gives English translations for some of the official posts in a glossary.{{sfnp|Standen|2007|pages=241-247}}\n\nVolumes 63-70 are tables including the lineage of the ruling [[Yel\u00fc]] clan as well as other clans in volume 63, tribes (\u90e8\u65cf) in volume 69, and vassal states (\u5c6c\u570b) in volume 70.\n\nNotable figures included in the Biographies section include [[Han Yanhui]], Liao chancellor of Han origin in volume 74; [[Zhao Yanshou]] general from the Later Tang who also served the Liao in volume 76; and Wang Jizhong \u738b\u7e7c\u5fe0, who helped broker the [[Chanyuan Treaty]] of 1004\u20131005 in volume 81.{{sfnp|Standen|2007|pages=158-166}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThe debate about the legacy of the Liao as a legitimate dynasty continued after the completion of the text. Around the time of publication [[Yang Weizhen]] stated that only the Song was a legitimate dynasty and the Liao and Jin were usurpers. {{sfnp|Chan|2014|page=89}} He continued to argue this point and composed an essay titled 'On legitimate Succession' \u6b63\u7d71\u8faf. Ming scholar Wang Zhu \u738b\u6d19 wrote an alterative history of the Song titled ''Verified History of the Song'' \u5b8b\u53f2\u8cea in which the Liao and Jin states were relegated to treatises on foreign states. However, Wang Chu's text received criticism itself from Qing scholars who viewed it as an intentional distortion of history. {{sfnp|Chan|2014|pages=98-100}} In addition, the text ''Great Outline of Historical Records'' by Ming scholar Shao Jingbang \u90b5\u7d93\u90a6 (1491-1561) gave the Liao and Jin the status of alien usurpers.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Wikisourcelang|zh|\u907c\u53f2|''History of Liao'' (in Chinese)}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Michal |last=Biran |title = The Empire of the Qara Khitai in Eurasian History: Between China and the Islamic World |location=Cambridge; New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2005 |ref=Biran }}\n* Marsone, Pierre. ''La Steppe et l\u2019Empire : la formation de la dynastie Khitan (Liao)'', Paris, Les Belles Lettres, 2011.\n* Hok-lam Chan. ''China & the Mongols: History and Legend under the Yuan and Ming''. Brookfield, VT: Ashgate Publishing, 1999.\n* ''Liao Shi'' (LS) \u907c\u53f2 (History of Liao). Tuotuo \u8131\u8131 et al. eds. Beijing: Zhonghua Shuju \u4e2d\u534e\u4e66\u5c40, 1974.\n* {{cite book |first=Naomi |last=Standen |title = Unbounded Loyalty: Frontier Crossing in Liao China |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii Press | year=2007 |ref = Standen }}\n* {{Xu Elina-Qian|2.1 Introduction to the Sources on the Pre-dynastic Khitan (pp.19-23) > The Liao shi, pp.&nbsp;22-23.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://chinesenotes.com/liaoshi.html ''History of Liao'' \u300a\u907c\u53f2\u300b] Chinese text with matching English vocabulary\n\n{{-}}\n{{Twenty-Four Canonical Histories}}\n{{Yuan dynasty topics}}\n{{Liao dynasty topics}}\n{{Portal bar|China|History|Books}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Liao}}\n[[Category:Twenty-Four Histories]]\n[[Category:14th-century history books]]\n[[Category:Khitan history]]\n[[Category:Yuan dynasty literature]]\n[[Category:History books about the Liao dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Chinese|title=''History of Liao''|t=\u907c\u53f2|s=\u8fbd\u53f2|p=Li\u00e1o Sh\u01d0|poj=Li\u00e2u-s\u00fa}}\nThe '''''History of Liao''''', or '''''Liao Shi''''' ('''''Li\u00e1o Sh\u01d0'''''), is a Chinese historical book compiled officially by the [[Mongol]] [[Yuan dynasty]] (1271\u20131368), under the direction of the historian [[Toqto'a (Yuan dynasty)|Toqto'a]] (Tuotuo), and finalized in 1344.<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\">Xu Elina-Qian, p.22</ref> Based on Khitan's primary sources and other previous official Chinese records, it exposes the [[Khitan people]], Khitan's tribal life and traditions, as well as the official histories of the [[Liao dynasty]] and its successor, the [[Qara Khitai|Western Liao dynasty]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" />\n\n== Main sources ==\n''History of Liao'' of 1344 was compiled using older sources, mainly: \n* the ''Shilu'' \u5be6\u9304 (Veritable Records), completed in the Khitan Liao dynasty (907-1125) under Yel\u00fc Yan \u8036\u5f8b\u513c's direction, no longer extant;\n* a draft ''Liao Shi'', compiled in the Jurchen [[Jin dynasty (1115-1234)|Jin dynasty]] under the direction of an official named Chen Daren \u9673\u5927\u4efb, never published and no longer extant;\n* and several other sources such as the [[Zizhi Tongjian]] (1080's), [[Qidan Guo Zhi]] and other descriptions of the Khitans in the previous dynastic histories ([[Wei Shu]], [[Sui Shu]], ...).\nThe ''Liao Shi'' contains 116 volumes,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> including 30 volumes of Imperial Annals, 32 volumes of Records of Institutions, 8 volumes of Tables, 48 volumes of Biographies and Descriptions, and 1 volume of Glossary of National Language \u570b\u8a9e\u89e3 Guoyijie (the [[Khitan language]]),<ref>{{cite book|title=Chinese History: A Manual|first=Endymion Porter|last=Wilkinson|others=|volume=Volume 52 of Harvard Yenching Institute Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard-Yenching Institute monograph series |issue=Issue 52 of Harvard-Yenching Institute monograph series| ISSN =0073-084X|editor-first=|editor-last=|edition=illustrated, revised|date=|year=2000|publisher=Harvard Univ Asia Center|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERnrQq0bsPYC&pg=PA864&dq=Qinding+Liao+Jin+Yuan+sanshi+guoyujie&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PskPVL60NdLhsATT24Bw&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Qinding%20Liao%20Jin%20Yuan%20sanshi%20guoyujie&f=false|page=864|isbn=0674002490|accessdate=24 April 2014| ref=harv }}</ref><ref>pp. 123-125 Howorth, H. H.. 1881. \"The Northern Frontagers of China. Part V. The Khitai or Khitans\". Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland 13 (2). Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland: 121\u201382. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25196875.</ref><ref name=\"YongPeng2008\">{{cite book|author1=Heming Yong|author2=Jing Peng|title=Chinese Lexicography : A History from 1046 BC to AD 1911: A History from 1046 BC to AD 1911|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NYFBtTUZFxEC&pg=PA382#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=14 August 2008|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-156167-2|pages=382\u2013}}</ref> which is a list of Khitan language words [[Transcription into Chinese characters|transcribed in Chinese characters]]. it is found in Chapter 116 - [https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u907c\u53f2/\u5377116 \u907c\u53f2/\u5377116].\n\n== Creation and reliability ==\nMany Chinese scholars of the time argued that the non-[[Han Chinese|Han]], \"barbarian\" Liao dynasty did not merit its own official history, but rather posited that the Liao histories should be an addendum to the history of the [[Song dynasty|Song]], which was ethnically [[Han Chinese]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> This was part of the larger dispute between the Mongol court and the Chinese literati scholars, in which the Chinese political theory whereby only one dynasty could be deemed legitimate at a time clashed with the Mongol's beliefs to the contrary.<ref>Hok-lam Chan, p.73</ref> Due to this dispute between two different political cultures, the ''Liao Shi'', as well as the histories of the concurrent [[Jin dynasty (1115-1234)|Jin]] and Song dynasties, was not officially compiled until 1343-1344, when the pro-Chinese Chief Councillor Toqto'a took up the pre-Yuan histories project again. In its final form, this project conceded to the Mongol court's desire to treat the Liao, Jin, and Song as equally legitimate dynasties. The compilation of the ''Liao Shi'' was finished in one year<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> by imperial historians, although without undergoing any but the most minimal of proofreadings.<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> Because of this, the ''Liao Shi'' and the other two pre-Yuan histories are known for their technical errors, lack of precision, inconsistencies in transcribing non-Chinese terms and names, and over-lapping subject matter.  Qing scholars [[Qian Daxin]] and Zhao Yi noted inconsistencies in the '''''History of Liao''''' in their works ''Study of the Discrepancies in the Twenty-two Standard Histories'' \u5eff\u4e8c\u53f2\u5284\u8a18 and ''Critical Notes on the Twenty-two Histories'' \u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\u53f2\u5284\u8a18.{{sfnp|Chan|2014|page=91}}\n<!-- Inside -->\nNonetheless, the ''Liao Shi'' provides a large amount of knowledge on Khitan's imperium's tribal politics and traditions. Since Yel\u00fc Yan's ''Shilu'' and Chen Daren's ''Liao Shi'' have been lost,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, p.22\" /> Toqto'a's ''Liao Shi'' is the only extant Chinese-style historical record of the Khitan empire.\n\n== Editions ==\nThe work of collation and punctuation have been done several times,<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23\">Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23</ref> by example in the Qianlong edition, the Nanjian edition, the Beijian edition, Baina edition and the Daoguang edition.<br />The nowadays commonly use edition is the Zhonghua Shuju Press edited ''Liao Shi'', under direction of the Khitan studies' specialists [[Feng Jiasheng]] and [[Chen Shu (scholar)|Chen Shu]], and based on the Baina edition. This Zhonghua Shuju Press version and its annotations also refer to other historical sources such as the [[Cefu Yuangui]], [[Zizhi Tongjian]], [[Xu Zizhi Tongjian Changbian]], [[Jiu Tangshu|Jiu]] & [[Xin Tangshu]], [[Jiu Wudai Shi|Jiu]] & [[Xin Wudai Shi]], [[History of Song|Song Shi]], [[Jin Shi]], [[Qidan Guo Zhi]] and [[Liao Wenhui]].<ref name=\"Xu Elina-Qian, pp.22-23\" /><ref name=\"LS, 1974\">\u907c\u53f2, \u8131\u8131, \u4e2d\u534e\u4e66\u5c40, 1974.</ref>\n\nThe History of Liao was translated into [[Manchu language|Manchu]] as {{MongolUnicode|\u1869\u1820\u1873\u182f\u1873\u1836\u1823\u1823<br />\u1864\u1860\u1875\u1860\u1828 {{zwj}}\u200d\u1873<br />\u1830\u1860\u1869\u1860\u1875\u1873}} (Wylie: ''Dailiyan gurun i suduri'', [[Transliterations of Manchu|M\u00f6llendorff]]: ''Dailiyan gurun i suduri'').\n\nThe [[Qing dynasty]] [[Qianlong Emperor]] erroneously identified the Khitan people and their language with the [[Solons]], leading him to use the [[Solon language]] to \"correct\" Chinese character transcriptions of Khitan names in the History of Liao in his \"Imperial Liao Jin Yuan Three Histories National Language Explanation\" (\u6b3d\u5b9a\u907c\u91d1\u5143\u4e09\u53f2\u570b\u8a9e\u89e3 Qinding Liao Jin Yuan sanshi guoyujie) project.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Crossley |first= Pamela Kyle |last2= Rawski |first2= Evelyn S. |date= Jun 1993 |title= A Profile of The Manchu Language in Ch'ing History |jstor= 2719468|journal= Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies |publisher= Harvard-Yenching Institute |volume=  53|issue= 1 |page=99 |doi= 10.2307/2719468 }}</ref>\n\nQianlong's \"corrections\" ended up compounding the errors and making the transcription of some foreign words even worse.<ref>{{cite book|title=Notices of the Medi\u00e6val Geography and History of Central and Western Asia| first=E.|last=Bretschneider|volume=|year=1876|edition=|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner & Company|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R98-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA6 |pages=5\u20136 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref> Marshall Broomhall wrote that ''So unscientific was this work that the K'ien-lung editions of the Liao, Kin, and Y\u00fcan histories are practically useless.''<ref name=\"Broomhall1910\">{{cite book|author=Marshall Broomhall|title=Islam in China: A Neglected Problem|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ObcNAAAAIAAJ|year=1910|publisher=Morgan & Scott, Limited|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ObcNAAAAIAAJ/page/n116 93]\u201394}}</ref> [[Emil Bretschneider]] demonstrated how the etymologies in the Qianlong edition were incorrect.<ref name=\"Bretschneider2013 2\">{{cite book|author=E. Bretschneider|title=Mediaeval Researches from Eastern Asiatic Sources: Fragments Towards the Knowledge of the Geography and History of Central and Western Asia from the 13th to the 17th Century:|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fc9YAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&dq=sagacity+savants+original+edition+calif+baghdad+correctly+ha+li+fa+uncorrupted+understood+turkish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwr6mZzfLOAhXCSSYKHShZB7EQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-38021-1|pages=182\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe annals are covered in Volumes 1-30 beginning with founder [[Abaoji]] (Taizu) in volumes 1-2. Volume 30 covers [[Yel\u00fc Dashi]], who fled and founded of the state of [[Qara Khitai]] also known as the Western Liao at the dissolution of the Liao dynasty. Biran describes  volume 30 of the text as the one of the most important sources for the history of the Qara Khitai.{{sfnp|Biran|2005|page=4}}\n\nTreatises are covered in volumes 31-62. The [[Administrative divisions of the Liao dynasty|administrative divisions of the Liao]] are described in volumes 37 through 41 under the title Geography (\u5730\u7406), organized by the five primary level circuits (\u9053). Official posts (\u767e\u5b98) are described in volumes 45-48. Standen gives English translations for some of the official posts in a glossary.{{sfnp|Standen|2007|pages=241-247}}\n\nVolumes 63-70 are tables including the lineage of the ruling [[Yel\u00fc]] clan as well as other clans in volume 63, tribes (\u90e8\u65cf) in volume 69, and vassal states (\u5c6c\u570b) in volume 70.\n\nNotable figures included in the Biographies section include [[Han Yanhui]], Liao chancellor of Han origin in volume 74; [[Zhao Yanshou]] general from the Later Tang who also served the Liao in volume 76; and Wang Jizhong \u738b\u7e7c\u5fe0, who helped broker the [[Chanyuan Treaty]] of 1004-1005 in volume 81.{{sfnp|Standen|2007|pages=158-166}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThe debate about the legacy of the Liao as a legitimate dynasty continued after the completion of the text. Around the time of publication [[Yang Weizhen]] stated that only the Song was a legitimate dynasty and the Liao and Jin were usurpers. {{sfnp|Chan|2014|page=89}} He continued to argue this point and composed an essay titled 'On legitimate Succession' \u6b63\u7d71\u8faf. Ming scholar Wang Zhu \u738b\u6d19 wrote an alterative history of the Song titled ''Verified History of the Song'' \u5b8b\u53f2\u8cea in which the Liao and Jin states were relegated to treatises on foreign states. However, Wang Chu's text received criticism itself from Qing scholars who viewed it as an intentional distortion of history. {{sfnp|Chan|2014|pages=98-100}} In addition, the text ''Great Outline of Historical Records'' by Ming scholar Shao Jingbang \u90b5\u7d93\u90a6 (1491-1561) gave the Liao and Jin the status of alien usurpers.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Wikisourcelang|zh|\u907c\u53f2|''History of Liao'' (in Chinese)}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Michal |last=Biran |title = The Empire of the Qara Khitai in Eurasian History: Between China and the Islamic World |location=Cambridge; New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2005 |ref=Biran }}\n* Marsone, Pierre. ''La Steppe et l\u2019Empire : la formation de la dynastie Khitan (Liao)'', Paris, Les Belles Lettres, 2011.\n* Hok-lam Chan. ''China & the Mongols: History and Legend under the Yuan and Ming''. Brookfield, VT: Ashgate Publishing, 1999.\n* ''Liao Shi'' (LS) \u907c\u53f2 (History of Liao). Tuotuo \u8131\u8131 et al. eds. Beijing: Zhonghua Shuju \u4e2d\u534e\u4e66\u5c40, 1974.\n* {{cite book |first=Naomi |last=Standen |title = Unbounded Loyalty: Frontier Crossing in Liao China |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii Press | year=2007 |ref = Standen }}\n* {{Xu Elina-Qian|2.1 Introduction to the Sources on the Pre-dynastic Khitan (pp.19-23) > The Liao shi, pp.&nbsp;22-23.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://chinesenotes.com/liaoshi.html ''History of Liao'' \u300a\u907c\u53f2\u300b] Chinese text with matching English vocabulary\n\n{{-}}\n{{Twenty-Four Canonical Histories}}\n{{Yuan dynasty topics}}\n{{Liao dynasty topics}}\n{{Portal bar|China|History|Books}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Liao}}\n[[Category:Twenty-Four Histories]]\n[[Category:14th-century history books]]\n[[Category:Khitan history]]\n[[Category:Yuan dynasty literature]]\n[[Category:History books about the Liao dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1004-1005 \u2192 1004\u20131005, 1343-1344 \u2192 1343\u20131344 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Liao"}
{"title_page": "Pinehurst Court", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name        = Pinehurst Court\n| native_name = \n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      = 1-3 Colville Gardens\n| image                = PinehurstCourt.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Pinehurst Court, showing [[All Saints Notting Hill|All Saints]] church in the background\n| map_type             = \n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = \n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = Mansion Block\n| architectural_style  = [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]]\n| structural_system    = Timber frame, brick, stucco.\n| cost                 = \n| ren_cost             =\n| location             = [[Notting Hill]]\n| location_town        =[[London]]\n| location_country     =[[United Kingdom]]\n| address              = \n| client               = \n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| coordinates          = \n| start_date           = c1870s\n| completion_date      = c1870s\n| inauguration_date    =\n| renovation_date      = \n| demolition_date      = \n| destruction_date     = \n| height               = \n| diameter             = \n| other_dimensions     = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = George Frederick Tippett\n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| other_designers      = Builder: George Frederick Tippett\n| quantity_surveyor    = \n| awards               = \n| ren_architect        =\n| ren_firm             =\n| ren_str_engineer     = \n| ren_serv_engineer    = \n| ren_civ_engineer     = \n| ren_oth_designers    = \n| ren_qty_surveyor     = \n| ren_awards           = \n| url                  = \n| references           = \n}}\n\n'''Pinehurst Court''' is a portered [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] mansion block at 1-9 [[Colville Gardens]], just off Colville Terrace and near the [[Portobello Market]] in [[Notting Hill]], [[London]], [[England]]. The terrace was initially built in the 1870s by the builder George Frederick Tippett, as single family residences, but from the 1880s the houses began to be subdivided into flats. By 1928 the neighbourhood was described as \"rapidly becoming poorer\", and by 1935 as a \"largely slum area\". The gentrification of [[Notting Hill]] in the 1980s and 1980s greatly improved the character of the building, which now forms a part of one of London's most fashionable neighbourhoods.\n\n==History==\n===19th Century origins===\nThe terrace was initially built in the 1870s by the builder [[George Frederick Tippett]], who also developed much of the rest of the neighbourhood. Tippet was an entrepreneur who combined the roles of ground landlord, developer, builder \"and probably architect as well\". <ref name=\"Survey\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49881#s7/ History of the Portobello and St Quintin Estates, Survey of London: Volume 37: Northern Kensington (1973)] Retrieved 5 April 2020</ref> The gardens, howevever, were smaller than some earlier ornamental gardens in the neighbourhood. The 1973 Survey of London described the gardens at 1-3 Colville Gardens as being \"a feeble imitation of the earlier and more spacious paddocks on the Ladbroke estate\". <ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe houses were intended as single family homes for the well-to-do but from the beginning it proved difficult to attract wealthy buyers to the area, and as early as 1888 the buildings began to be subdivided into flats.<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\">O'Malley, p.33</ref>  In 1885 Tippett was declared bankrupt. He attributed his failure to \"his inability to let a large portion of his property and to the pressure of secured creditors\". Gradually the character of the buildings changed as wealthier tenants left the area. By 1888 two of Tippet's houses in Colville Gardens had already been sub-divided into flats. <ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\n===1920s and 1930s===\nBy 1928 the neighbourhood was described as \"rapidly becoming poorer\", and by 1935 as a \"largely slum area... large houses turned into one-room tenements and small flats\". \n\n===World War II===\nFurther decline set in as many residents moved away during [[World War II]] to escape [[The Blitz]].<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\"/> One of the buildings at the end of the terrace was destroyed during a bombing raid; it has since been rebuilt in the modern style. The same raid severely damaged other neighbouring buildings including [[All Saints Notting Hill|All Saints Church]].\n\n===1950s===\nIn 1953 1-9 Colville Gardens was bought by Fernbank Investments Ltd (a subsidiary of Davies Investments Ltd) for \u00a38,000.<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\" /> Some questionable business practices followed, mostly involving attempts to displace sitting tenants (in some cases by intimidation) which however significantly increased the income from the property. At the same time the quality of the building deteriorated, and in around 1966 some of the residents began to approach the Council in order to attempt to improve living conditions.\n\n===1960s===\nIn 1967 Fernbank Investments declared bankruptcy. Its owner, Bowen Davies, took his own life, saying that he had \"caused suffering... to very many, and the burden on my conscience is intolerable\".<ref>O'Malley, 38</ref> \n\nIn October 1967 1-9 Colville Gardens was sold to another investment company, Trade and General Investments (Bahamas) Ltd, for \u00a365,000.<ref>O'Malley, 101</ref> The building continued to deteriorate and in February 1969 it was again sold, this time to Cledro Developments for \u00a3120,000, whose Director Robert Gubay described conditions in the buildings as \"truly terrible\".<ref>O'Malley, \u00b4103</ref> In 1970 the block was sold to Crown Agents of Overseas territories, who renamed the building Trident House. The building was then again sold, changing hands several times before being purchased by Elkington's (PIF) Ltd in 1972 and renamed \"Pinehurst Court\". Elkington's began to invest in the building, selling off the flats on long leases, mostly to the occupying tenants.<ref>O'Malley, 104</ref>\n\n===Modern Revival===\nOver recent years the quality of the building gradually improved, reflecting the general revival of Notting Hill.\n\nToday the building comprises around 105 one and two bedroom flats, mostly leased to private tenants on long leases of 100 years or more. The building is currently well maintained and forms a part of one of London's most fashionable neighbourhoods.\n\n==References==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=U6p0VR12ZSgC&pg=PA41&dq=colville+gardens&hl=en&ei=bRasTtqgOIec-waI6onMDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=colville%20gardens&f=false Holmes, Chris, p.41, ''Housing, Equality and Choice'' ] Retrieved October 2011\n* O'Malley, Jan, ''The Politics of Community Action in Notting Hill'', Spokesman Press, 1977\n*''The Portobello and St. Quintin estates'', Survey of London: volume 37: Northern Kensington (1973)\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49881#s7/ History of the Portobello and St Quintin Estates] Retrieved February 20, 2010\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{coord|51.5157|-0.2029|type:landmark_region:GB-KEC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Notting Hill]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name        = Pinehurst Court\n| native_name = \n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      = 1-3 Colville Gardens\n| image                = PinehurstCourt.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Pinehurst Court, showing [[All Saints Notting Hill|All Saints]] church in the background\n| map_type             = \n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = \n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = Mansion Block\n| architectural_style  = [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]]\n| structural_system    = Timber frame, brick, stucco.\n| cost                 = \n| ren_cost             =\n| location             = [[Notting Hill]]\n| location_town        =[[London]]\n| location_country     =[[United Kingdom]]\n| address              = \n| client               = \n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| coordinates          = \n| start_date           = c1870s\n| completion_date      = c1870s\n| inauguration_date    =\n| renovation_date      = \n| demolition_date      = \n| destruction_date     = \n| height               = \n| diameter             = \n| other_dimensions     = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = George Frederick Tippett\n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| other_designers      = Builder: George Frederick Tippett\n| quantity_surveyor    = \n| awards               = \n| ren_architect        =\n| ren_firm             =\n| ren_str_engineer     = \n| ren_serv_engineer    = \n| ren_civ_engineer     = \n| ren_oth_designers    = \n| ren_qty_surveyor     = \n| ren_awards           = \n| url                  = \n| references           = \n}}\n\n'''Pinehurst Court''' is a portered [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] mansion block at 1-9 [[Colville Gardens]], just off Colville Terrace and near the [[Portobello Market]] in [[Notting Hill]], [[London]], [[England]]. The terrace was initially built in the 1870s by the builder George Frederick Tippett, as single family residences, but from the 1880s the houses began to be subdivided into flats. By 1928 the neighbourhood was described as \"rapidly becoming poorer\", and by 1935 as a \"largely slum area\". The gentrification of [[Notting Hill]] in the 1980s and 1980s greatly improved the character of the building, which now forms a part of one of London's most fashionable neighbourhoods.\n\n==History==\n===19th Century origins===\nThe terrace was initially built in the 1870s by the builder [[George Frederick Tippett]], who also developed much of the rest of the neighbourhood. Tippet was an entrepreneur who combined the roles of ground landlord, developer, builder \"and probably architect as well\". <ref name=\"Survey\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49881#s7/ History of the Portobello and St Quintin Estates, Survey of London: Volume 37: Northern Kensington (1973)] Retrieved 5 April 2020</ref> The gardens, howevever, were smaller than some earlier ornamental gardens in the neighbourhood. The 1973 Survey of London described the gardens at 1-3 Colville Gardens as being \"a feeble imitation of the earlier and more spacious paddocks on the Ladbroke estate\". <ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe houses were intended as single family homes for the well-to-do but from the beginning it proved difficult to attract wealthy buyers to the area, and as early as 1888 the buildings began to be subdivided into flats.<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\">O'Malley, p.33</ref>  In 1885 Tippett was declared bankrupt. He attributed his failure to \"his inability to let a large portion of his property and to the pressure of secured creditors\". Gradually the character of the buildings changed as wealthier tenants left the area. By 1888 two houses at 1-3 Colville Gardens had already been sub-divided into flats. <ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\n===1920s and 1930s===\nBy 1928 the neighbourhood was described as \"rapidly becoming poorer\", and by 1935 as a \"largely slum area... large houses turned into one-room tenements and small flats\". \n\n===World War II===\nFurther decline set in as many residents moved away during [[World War II]] to escape [[The Blitz]].<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\"/> One of the buildings at the end of the terrace was destroyed during a bombing raid; it has since been rebuilt in the modern style. The same raid severely damaged other neighbouring buildings including [[All Saints Notting Hill|All Saints Church]].\n\n===1950s===\nIn 1953 1-9 Colville Gardens was bought by Fernbank Investments Ltd (a subsidiary of Davies Investments Ltd) for \u00a38,000.<ref name=\"O'Malley p.33\" /> Some questionable business practices followed, mostly involving attempts to displace sitting tenants (in some cases by intimidation) which however significantly increased the income from the property. At the same time the quality of the building deteriorated, and in around 1966 some of the residents began to approach the Council in order to attempt to improve living conditions.\n\n===1960s===\nIn 1967 Fernbank Investments declared bankruptcy. Its owner, Bowen Davies, took his own life, saying that he had \"caused suffering... to very many, and the burden on my conscience is intolerable\".<ref>O'Malley, 38</ref> \n\nIn October 1967 1-9 Colville Gardens was sold to another investment company, Trade and General Investments (Bahamas) Ltd, for \u00a365,000.<ref>O'Malley, 101</ref> The building continued to deteriorate and in February 1969 it was again sold, this time to Cledro Developments for \u00a3120,000, whose Director Robert Gubay described conditions in the buildings as \"truly terrible\".<ref>O'Malley, \u00b4103</ref> In 1970 the block was sold to Crown Agents of Overseas territories, who renamed the building Trident House. The building was then again sold, changing hands several times before being purchased by Elkington's (PIF) Ltd in 1972 and renamed \"Pinehurst Court\". Elkington's began to invest in the building, selling off the flats on long leases, mostly to the occupying tenants.<ref>O'Malley, 104</ref>\n\n===Modern Revival===\nOver recent years the quality of the building gradually improved, reflecting the general revival of Notting Hill.\n\nToday the building comprises around 105 one and two bedroom flats, mostly leased to private tenants on long leases of 100 years or more. The building is currently well maintained and forms a part of one of London's most fashionable neighbourhoods.\n\n==References==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=U6p0VR12ZSgC&pg=PA41&dq=colville+gardens&hl=en&ei=bRasTtqgOIec-waI6onMDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=colville%20gardens&f=false Holmes, Chris, p.41, ''Housing, Equality and Choice'' ] Retrieved October 2011\n* O'Malley, Jan, ''The Politics of Community Action in Notting Hill'', Spokesman Press, 1977\n*''The Portobello and St. Quintin estates'', Survey of London: volume 37: Northern Kensington (1973)\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49881#s7/ History of the Portobello and St Quintin Estates] Retrieved February 20, 2010\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{coord|51.5157|-0.2029|type:landmark_region:GB-KEC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Notting Hill]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n", "name_user": "Asteuartw", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e19th Century origins:tidy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinehurst_Court"}
{"title_page": "Corabia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Olt\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Olt County\n|official_name=Corabia\n|image_map=Corabia jud Olt.png\n|image_shield=ROU OT Corabia CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Iulic\u0103 Oane<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-05 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=123.19\n|coordinates   = {{coord|43|46|25|N|24|30|12|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primariacorabia.ro}}\n}}\n\n'''Corabia''' ({{IPA-ro|ko\u02c8rabi.a}}) is a small [[Danube]] port located in [[Olt County]], [[Romania]], which used to be part of the now-dissolved [[Romana\u0163i County]] before [[World War II]]. Across the Danube from Corabia lies the [[Bulgaria]]n village of [[Gigen]]. \n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |9124\n|1930 |8857\n|1948 |10772\n|1956 |11502\n|1966 |14502\n|1977 |19705\n|1992 |22386\n|2002 |21932\n|2011 |16441\n}}\n\nBeneath Corabia, around the former village of Celei, lie the remains of [[Sucidava]], an old Dacian and Roman town and fortress. Near the town, Emperor [[Constantine the Great]] built the longest European bridge over the Danube (2437 m). The bridge was destroyed during the Avar invasions, probably in the 7th century.  The ruins also contain an old Roman bath and an old basilica.  The name ''Corabia'' reflects the fact that the new settlement was built from the remains of a wrecked [[Republic of Genoa|Genoan]] ship (''corabia'' is the [[Romanian language]] term for \"[[sailing ship]]\", specifically used for \"[[galley]]\"). It became a thriving port in the 1880s. \n\nUnder the [[Communist Romania|communist regime]], Corabia developed as a considerable manufacturing town, with a [[sugar mill]], furniture factory, [[Tanning (leather)|tannery]], a fiber manufacturing plant, and various other facilities. However, in more recent times the town's population has dwindled. Many inhabitants have migrated to larger towns in the wake of the closure of many of Corabia's factories.\n\n==Geography==\nCorabia is still one of the central spots of Olt County; the town administers two villages, Tudor Vladimirescu and V\u00e2rtopu. The town houses a [[Football (soccer)|football]] club, several shops and bars, the remains of the Roman ''[[Castra|castrum]]'' ''[[Sucidava]]'', dating back to the [[Roman Empire|Roman period]] and featuring the \"Secret Fountain\" (an unusual piece of engineering); the Holy Trinity Orthodox Cathedral (one of the largest buildings of its kind in Romania), as well a monumental statue in the middle of the town square commemorating the use of Corabia's facilities in the initial attack during the [[Romanian War of Independence]]. Corabia also has an important archaeological museum with, ''inter alia'', a remarkable collection of Roman pottery. From the town harbour one can make trips along the Danube, with stops at the nearby B\u0103loi Island.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Pavel Chihaia]]\n* [[Theodor Danetti]]\n* [[Nicolae Dobrescu]]\n* [[Valentin Al. Georgescu]]\n* [[Pola Ill\u00e9ry]]\n* [[\u0218erban Ionescu]]\n* [[Theodor D. Ionescu]]\n* [[Virgil Mazilescu]]\n* [[Ion Oblemenco]]\n* [[Ion R\u00eemaru]]\n* [[Robert S\u0103ceanu]]\n* [[Vladimir Screciu]]\n* [[Cristina V\u0103rzaru]]\n* [[\u0218tefan Voitec]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Casa de cultura - Culture House and Corabia Museum.jpg|Culture House and Archaeological Museum\nImage:Corabia.jpg|City center\nImage:FalezaPark.jpg|Danube at Corabia\nImage:Monument eroilor.jpg|1877 Independence War Heroes Monument\nImage:Str 1 Mai.jpg|1st May Street\nImage:Sucidava fantana.jpg|Sucidava's Secret Fountain\nImage:Turnul cu ceas - Corabia Saint Trinity Cathedral.jpg|Holy Trinity Cathedral\n</gallery>\n\n{{commons category|Corabia}}\n\n{{Olt County}}\n{{Danube}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Danube]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Olt County]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Corabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Olt\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Olt County\n|official_name=Corabia\n|image_map=Corabia jud Olt.png\n|image_shield=ROU OT Corabia CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Iulica Oane\n|leader_party=[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n|area_total_km2=123.19\n|coordinates   = {{coord|43|46|25|N|24|30|12|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primariacorabia.ro}}\n}}\n\n'''Corabia''' ({{IPA-ro|ko\u02c8rabi.a}}) is a small [[Danube]] port located in [[Olt County]], [[Romania]], which used to be part of the now-dissolved [[Romana\u0163i County]] before [[World War II]]. Across the Danube from Corabia lies the [[Bulgaria]]n village of [[Gigen]]. \n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |9124\n|1930 |8857\n|1948 |10772\n|1956 |11502\n|1966 |14502\n|1977 |19705\n|1992 |22386\n|2002 |21932\n|2011 |16441\n}}\n\nBeneath Corabia, around the former village of Celei, lie the remains of [[Sucidava]], an old Dacian and Roman town and fortress. Near the town, Emperor [[Constantine the Great]] built the longest European bridge over the Danube (2437 m). The bridge was destroyed during the Avar invasions, probably in the 7th century.  The ruins also contain an old Roman bath and an old basilica.  The name ''Corabia'' reflects the fact that the new settlement was built from the remains of a wrecked [[Republic of Genoa|Genoan]] ship (''corabia'' is the [[Romanian language]] term for \"[[sailing ship]]\", specifically used for \"[[galley]]\"). It became a thriving port in the 1880s. \n\nUnder the [[Communist Romania|communist regime]], Corabia developed as a considerable manufacturing town, with a [[sugar mill]], furniture factory, [[Tanning (leather)|tannery]], a fiber manufacturing plant, and various other facilities. However, in more recent times the town's population has dwindled. Many inhabitants have migrated to larger towns in the wake of the closure of many of Corabia's factories.\n\n==Geography==\nCorabia is still one of the central spots of Olt County; the town administers two villages, Tudor Vladimirescu and V\u00e2rtopu. The town houses a [[Football (soccer)|football]] club, several shops and bars, the remains of the Roman ''[[Castra|castrum]]'' ''[[Sucidava]]'', dating back to the [[Roman Empire|Roman period]] and featuring the \"Secret Fountain\" (an unusual piece of engineering); the Holy Trinity Orthodox Cathedral (one of the largest buildings of its kind in Romania), as well a monumental statue in the middle of the town square commemorating the use of Corabia's facilities in the initial attack during the [[Romanian War of Independence]]. Corabia also has an important archaeological museum with, ''inter alia'', a remarkable collection of Roman pottery. From the town harbour one can make trips along the Danube, with stops at the nearby B\u0103loi Island.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Pavel Chihaia]]\n* [[Theodor Danetti]]\n* [[Nicolae Dobrescu]]\n* [[Valentin Al. Georgescu]]\n* [[Pola Ill\u00e9ry]]\n* [[\u0218erban Ionescu]]\n* [[Theodor D. Ionescu]]\n* [[Virgil Mazilescu]]\n* [[Ion Oblemenco]]\n* [[Ion R\u00eemaru]]\n* [[Robert S\u0103ceanu]]\n* [[Vladimir Screciu]]\n* [[Cristina V\u0103rzaru]]\n* [[\u0218tefan Voitec]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Casa de cultura - Culture House and Corabia Museum.jpg|Culture House and Archaeological Museum\nImage:Corabia.jpg|City center\nImage:FalezaPark.jpg|Danube at Corabia\nImage:Monument eroilor.jpg|1877 Independence War 